ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='We have a fairly clear picture now. Let\'s plan the modifications.\n\
n### Issue 1: SQL named params -> positional `?`\nWe need to replace all `:lat`,
`:lng`, `:maxDist`, `:userId`, `:preferredGender`, `:myGender`, `:limit` in the 
SQL string with `?`, and ensure the parameter array matches the order of placeho
lders exactly.\n\nLet\'s count placeholders in the SQL. The current SQL (lines 1
60-216) includes these named parameters. We need to replace them in order and pr
ovide the correct array.\n\nWe must be careful: the same parameter may appear mu
ltiple times. For positional `?`, we must repeat the value in the array for each
occurrence.\n\nLet\'s count occurrences manually:\n- `:lat` appears in:\n  - `CO
S(RADIANS(:lat))` (line 166)\n  - `SIN(RADIANS(:lat))` (line 167)\n  - `COS(RADI
ANS(:lat))` (line 174)\n  - `SIN(RADIANS(:lat))` (line 175)\n  - `COS(RADIANS(:l
at))` (line 198)\n  - `SIN(RADIANS(:lat))` (line 199)\n  Total: 6 times.\n- `:ln
g` appears in:\n  - `COS(RADIANS(up.longitude) - RADIANS(:lng))` (line 166)\n  -
`COS(RADIANS(up.longitude) - RADIANS(:lng))` (line 174)\n  - `COS(RADIANS(up.lon
gitude) - RADIANS(:lng))` (line 198)\n  Total: 3 times.\n- `:maxDist` appears in
:\n  - `LEAST(..., :maxDist)` (line 177)\n  - `/ :maxDist)` (line 178)\n  - `<= 
:maxDist` (line 200)\n  Total: 3 times.\n- `:userId` appears in:\n  - `u.id != :
userId` (line 192)\n  - `SELECT target_id FROM match_actions WHERE actor_id = :u
serId` (line 202)\n  - `SELECT actor_id FROM match_actions WHERE target_id = :us
erId` (line 204)\n  - `SELECT user_a_id FROM matches WHERE user_b_id = :userId` 
(line 206)\n  - `SELECT user_b_id FROM matches WHERE user_a_id = :userId` (line 
208)\n  - `SELECT blocked_id FROM blocks WHERE blocker_id = :userId` (line 210)\
n  - `SELECT blocker_id FROM blocks WHERE blocked_id = :userId` (line 212)\n  To
tal: 7 times.\n- `:preferredGender` appears in:\n  - `(:preferredGender = \'both
\' OR up.gender = :preferredGender)` (line 195)\n  Total: 2 times.\n- `:myGender
` appears in:\n  - `up.preferred_gender = :myGender` (line 196)\n  Total: 1 time
.\n- `:limit` appears in:\n  - `LIMIT :limit` (line 215)\n  Total: 1 time.\n\nTo
tal placeholders = 6+3+3+7+2+1+1 = 23.\n\nThe current param array (lines 218-235
) has 16 entries, which is insufficient even if named params were supported (whi
ch they aren\'t). We need to create an array with 23 entries in the exact order.
\n\nLet\'s map the order as the placeholders appear from top to bottom in the SQ
L string:\n\n1. `:lat` (line 166 first)\n2. `:lng` (line 166)\n3. `:lat` (line 1
67)\n4. `:lat` (line 174)\n5. `:lng` (line 174)\n6. `:lat` (line 175)\n7. `:maxD
ist` (line 177)\n8. `:maxDist` (line 178)\n9. `:userId` (line 192)\n10. `:prefer
redGender` (line 195 first)\n11. `:preferredGender` (line 195 second)\n12. `:myG
ender` (line 196)\n13. `:lat` (line 198)\n14. `:lng` (line 198)\n15. `:lat` (lin
e 199)\n16. `:maxDist` (line 200)\n17. `:userId` (line 202)\n18. `:userId` (line
204)\n19. `:userId` (line 206)\n20. `:userId` (line 208)\n21. `:userId` (line 21
0)\n22. `:userId` (line 212)\n23. `:limit` (line 215)\n\nSo the array should be:
\n[\n  profile.latitude,   // 1\n  profile.longitude,  // 2\n  profile.latitude,
  // 3\n  profile.latitude,   // 4\n  profile.longitude,  // 5\n  profile.latitu
de,   // 6\n  maxDistance,        // 7\n  maxDistance,        // 8\n  userId,   
         // 9\n  preferredGender,    // 10\n  preferredGender,    // 11\n  myGen
der,           // 12\n  profile.latitude,   // 13\n  profile.longitude,  // 14\n
 profile.latitude,   // 15\n  maxDistance,        // 16\n  userId,             /
/ 17\n  userId,             // 18\n  userId,             // 19\n  userId,       
     // 20\n  userId,             // 21\n  userId,             // 22\n  limit,  
           // 23\n]\n\nLet\'s verify: lat appears at indices 1,3,4,6,13,15 => 6 
times. lng at 2,5,14 => 3 times. maxDist at 7,8,16 => 3 times. userId at 9,17,18
,19,20,21,22 => 7 times. preferredGender at 10,11 => 2 times. myGender at 12 => 
1. limit at 23 => 1. Total 23.\n\nThat seems correct.\n\n### Issue 2: Socket.io 
Gateway JWT auth\nWe need to validate JWT in `handleConnection`. We can either i
mplement a custom guard for WS or manually verify in `handleConnection`. Since t
he review mentions `@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard)` WS adaptation, but the existing `J
wtAuthGuard` uses `context.switchToHttp().getRequest()` which won\'t work for WS
. The simplest fix that satisfies the requirement is to manually verify `client.
handshake.auth.token` (or `client.handshake.headers.authorization`) inside `hand
leConnection`, extract `userId` from the JWT payload, and join the room. If inva
lid, disconnect the client.\n\nWe should also remove `userId` from query paramet
ers and update the docs. However, the mobile client currently passes `query: {\'
userId\': userId}`. We need to update the mobile client to pass `auth: {\'token\
': token}` instead? But the review only says: "同步更新 docs/api/socket-events.m
d 中的连接参数说明". It doesn\'t explicitly say to update the mobile client code
to pass token, but logically if we remove query-based userId, the mobile client 
must pass the token. The review says: "认证通过后，从 JWT payload 中读取 userId
，禁止客户端通过 query 参数传入 userId". So we need to update the mobile client 
to stop passing userId via query and instead pass token via auth (or headers). T
he review mentions minor issue 12 about URL regex in matching_socket_client.dart
. So we should update that file anyway. We should change it to pass auth token.\
n\nBut the mobile client needs access to the auth token. How does it get it? We 
need to see if there is an auth repository or token storage. Let\'s search for t
oken storage in the mobile app.',
